>’), or possibly from an unattested Old English word <i>bing</i> ‘a kettle-shaped hollow’, + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Irish (Ulster, of Scottish origin): altered form of   Bigham  .","American shortened and altered form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames such as   Bingenheimer  ."]},{"name":"Gain","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname for a cunning person, from <i>Engaine</i>, which is based on Old French <i>engaigne</i> ‘ingenuity, cunning, trickery’.","English: habitiational name from any of various places called after the <i>Engain</i> family, including Colne Engaine and Gaynes Park (Essex), d'Engaine's Farm (Cambridgeshire), and Aston Ingham (Hereford). <i>Engaine</i> (see 1 above) was the name of a powerful Norman family with lands in several counties. The original form of the surname has since died out, surviving as <i>Gain</i> and its variants. There has also been considerable confusion with   Ingham  .","French: nickname from a noun derivative of Old French <i>gaainier</i> ‘to obtain, gain, win’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Ingham was born in 1250, in Ingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Oliver de Ingham, was 37 and his mother, Mrs. Elizabeth De Ingham, was 45. He had at least 1 son with Margery De Ingham. He died on 14 April 1310, in his hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1250–14 April 1310":"1250–14. aprill 1310","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1266–Female":"1266–Surnud","1287–1344":"1287–1344","1213–1282":"1213–1282","1205–1292":"1205–1292","1205":"1205","1213":"1213","1344":"1344","1266":"1266","1310":"1310","1287":"1287","14 April 1310":"14. aprill 1310","1250":"1250","15 Jul 1282":"15. juuli 1282","1282":"1282","about 1287":"umbes 1287","1292":"1292","Ingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Ingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ingham, Smallburgh, N